<section class="page-head">
  <h1>About this site</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A hub for {{ site.college }} faculty to learn about UCF Faculty Senate committees,
    see where CECS is represented, and volunteer for open seats.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="prose">
  <h2>Why committee service matters</h2>
  <p>
    The UCF Faculty Senate staffs three classes of committees and councils — operational
    committees, curricular committees and councils, and joint university committees. They
    set policy on curriculum, budget, research, promotion and tenure, technology, the academic
    calendar, and more. When CECS faculty serve, engineering and computer science perspectives
    are part of those decisions.
  </p>

  <h2>How members are chosen</h2>
  <p>
    Volunteers from this site are compiled by the CECS Faculty Senate representative and put
    forward for nomination through the Faculty Senate's Committee on Committees. Volunteering
    expresses interest; it is not a guarantee of placement. Terms are typically two or three years.
  </p>

  <h2>Your privacy</h2>
  <p>
    The volunteer form collects your name, UCF email, department, rank, committee interests, and
    optional notes. Your <strong>name and department may appear publicly</strong> on this site to
    show momentum and avoid duplicate sign-ups. Your <strong>email and notes are kept private</strong>
    and are used only by the CECS representative for follow-up.
  </p>

  <h2>How the site works</h2>
  <p>
    This is a static site hosted on GitHub Pages. Committee data lives in editable files in the
    repository. Volunteer submissions are collected through Formspree and synced back into the site
    as JSON on a schedule, so the committee pages reflect who has signed up.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <p>
    Reach out to <a href="mailto:{{ site.contactEmail }}">{{ site.contactName }}</a>, or browse the
    <a href="{{ site.committeesReferenceUrl }}" target="_blank" rel="noopener">official UCF Faculty Senate committees page ↗</a>.
  </p>
</section>
